Stocks in South Africa Snap Three-Day Drop, Led by Anglo American, Sasol

-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 
2011-05-06T15:55:51Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-06/stocks-in-south-africa-fall-for-fourth-day-led-by-bhp-billiton-and-sasol.html
The FTSE/JSE  Africa  All Share Index
snapped three days of losses, gaining 296.69, or 0.9 percent, to
31,878.83 at the 5 p.m. close of trade in Johannesburg and
paring its loss to 2.9 percent in the week.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  Anglo American Plc (AAL)  , a diversified mining company
that makes up 10 percent of the benchmark  stock index , jumped
the most since April 20, rising 7 rand, or 2.1 percent, to 334
rand. The  U.S. economy  added more jobs than forecast in April,
easing concern that higher fuel prices are slowing the economic
recovery. Payrolls increased by 244,000 workers last month, the
Labor Department said today in  Washington .  Kumba Iron Ore Ltd. (KIO) 
, the iron ore-producing unit of Anglo American,
advanced 13 rand, or 2.9 percent, to 462.50 rand, the highest
close since May 3.  BHP Billiton Plc (BIL)  , the world’s biggest mining
company, snapped six days of losses, gaining 1.86 rand, or 0.7
percent, to 266.25 rand.  Naspers Ltd. (NPN)  , Africa’s largest media company, rose
the most since April 20, adding 12 rand, or 3.2 percent, to
383.50 rand.  Harmony Gold Mining Ltd. (HAR SJ), Africa’s third-largest
producer of the metal, advanced 1.35 rand, or 1.5 percent, to
94.10 rand, snapping three days of decreases. Gold rose after
three days of losses.  Gold Fields Ltd. (GFI)  , the continent’s
second-largest producer of the metal, snapped three days of
declines, rising 50 cents, or 0.5 percent, to 109 rand.  MTN Group Ltd. (MTN)  , Africa’s largest mobile-phone
operator, declined 1.40 rand, or 1 percent, to 142 rand, the
lowest close since April 26. The company said its assets in
Guinea Conakry have been placed under administration by the
government following a regulatory dispute.  Sasol Ltd. (SOL)  , the world’s biggest maker of motor
fuel from coal, rose to the highest since May 4, jumping 6.50
rand, or 1.8 percent, to 361 rand. Oil increased for the first
time in five days, gaining 1.4 percent to $101.22 a barrel.  To contact the reporter on this story:
